We then need to find the remainder of this total \(K\) when divided by 10. 1. **Understanding the Sequences**: - Each element in the set \(\{1, 2, \ldots, 10\}\) can be added to the subsets at any position \(i\) (from 1 to \(n\)) and remains in all subsequent subsets. - For each element, the number of ways to choose when it is added (starting at position \(i\) and remaining present) is \(n\) choices for each element not in the starting subset. 2. **Counting the Sequences**: - For each \(n\), the number of sequences of length \(n\) is \((n + 1)^{10}\). This is derived from the binomial theorem, where the sum over all subsets \(S\) of \(n^{10 - |S|}\) simplifies to \((n + 1)^{10}\). 3. **Summing Over All \(n\)**: - The total number \(K\) is the sum of \((n + 1)^{10}\) for \(n\) from 1 to 10: \[ K = \sum_{n=1}^{10} (n + 1)^{10} \] 4. **Calculating Modulo 10**: - Compute each term \((n + 1)^{10} \mod 10\) for \(n\) from 1 to 10: - \(2^{10} \equiv 4 \mod 10\) - \(3^{10} \equiv 9 \mod 10\) - \(4^{10} \equiv 6 \mod 10\) - \(5^{10} \equiv 5 \mod 10\) - \(6^{10} \equiv 6 \mod 10\) - \(7^{10} \equiv 9 \mod 10\) - \(8^{10} \equiv 4 \mod 10\) - \(9^{10} \equiv 1 \mod 10\) - \(10^{10} \equiv 0 \mod 10\) - \(11^{10} \equiv 1 \mod 10\) 5. **Summing the Results**: - Summing these results modulo 10: \[ 4 + 9 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 9 + 4 + 1 + 0 + 1 = 45 \equiv 5 \mod 10 \] Thus, the remainder when \(K\) is divided by 10 is \(\boxed{5}\).
